{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f60abb6f-56ba-41a9-8889-c9bc19c93bde","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — re-installs the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer packages needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK version changed → `dotnet workload update`. Workload files got corrupted → `dotnet workload repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf issues persist after updating, also verify the workload is installed:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9bcc5061-0df8-47b3-a3c5-542229161820","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase for this.","outputTokens":257,"requestId":"9439:11529C:13AEA59:16156B7:6A066FFF"},"id":"948de1ca-891d-4e1b-8afd-a8a3fce3c8b1","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:59:51.304Z","parentId":"1d0ddad5-db0a-4163-b2e4-0b11bf44c1d6"}
